				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">Re: How to handle runners when kiting??<a name="41690"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">May 24 04 9:47 AM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span>Most mobs suitable for swarm-kiting are sociable, and as such won't run if they have colleagues near them (of the same mob-type). Some other mobs (especially undead) are just plain dumb, don't recognise a superior force when they see it and never run at all<img src="/skins/default/images/emotions/emotion-1.gif" border="0" alt="Smiley" hspace="2" />
<br />

<br />
I'd restrict your swarmkiting to these 2 types, otherwise things can get messy. However, if you do need to swarmkite a mix of mobs and some of them will run, just keep snare ready. When they are about to run, hit snare and then finish them off with chants/DDs (you'll get chants later on).
<br />

<br />
Edit: Noticed you're level 25 so guessing you're not swarmkiting yet, so guessing you are doing AE kiting? Same principle applies though, you want to get social mobs that will support each other, and keep them close together. If one does drop out, snare it and focus on killing it asap (with your AEs/DD, and later on with chants). Try to keep your kites down to groups of similar mobs, or 2 types at most. I think you're just about hitting iceclad snowcougar level now which is a great place for AE kiting.</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
